  "prompt": "What were the causes and effects of the Boxer Rebellion? How did it affect the Qing Dynasty?",
  "response": "The Boxer Rebellion (1899-1901) was a complex anti-foreign and anti-colonial uprising in China with significant consequences for the Qing Dynasty:\n\nCauses:\n1. Foreign Imperialism\n- Western powers and Japan had gained extensive economic and territorial concessions in China\n- Unequal treaties imposed harsh conditions on China\n- Foreign missionaries and economic interests were seen as threatening Chinese culture and sovereignty\n\n2. Economic Hardship\n- Severe drought and economic challenges\n- Foreign economic dominance disrupted traditional Chinese economic structures\n- Many Chinese felt economically marginalized\n\n3. Cultural Resentment\n- Growing anger against foreign influence\n- Perception that Western powers were undermining traditional Chinese values\n- Belief that foreign presence was weakening Chinese society\n\nEffects on the Qing Dynasty:\n1. Weakening of Imperial Authority\n- Qing Dynasty initially opposed the Boxers but later supported them\n- Massive military defeat by international powers\n- Significant loss of credibility and power\n\n2. Economic Consequences\n- Enormous war reparations imposed by foreign powers\n- Further economic dependency on foreign nations\n- Substantial financial strain on the Chinese government\n\n3. Political Transformation\n- Accelerated calls for modernization and reform\n- Undermined traditional imperial governance\n- Contributed to the eventual collapse of the Qing Dynasty in 1911\n\nInternational Consequences:\n- Demonstrated the vulnerability of China to foreign intervention\n- Increased international tensions\n- Exposed the weakness of the Qing government\n\nThe Boxer Rebellion was a crucial turning point in late Qing Dynasty history, highlighting the deep tensions between traditional Chinese society and growing foreign influence.",
